  Fabio Massimo Capogrosso,<br>
  Everyone has his story
subtitle1: >+
  Fabio Massimo Capogrosso, the first Composer-in-Residence of the Filarmonica
  “Arturo Toscanini” of Parma, is widely regarded as one of the most
  accomplished composers of his generation.




  A composer of symphonic, chamber, theatrical, and film music, he has been
  featured by leading national and international institutions and festivals,
  including the Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia, Teatro alla Scala in
  Milan, Teatro La Fenice in Venice, the IUC Concert Series, the Scuola Normale
  Superiore in Pisa, the San Francisco International Piano Festival, the Rebecca
  Penneys Piano Festival, Villa Pennisi in Musica, Teatro Grande in Brescia, the
  University of Michigan, and the Barness Music Recital Hall at the University
  of South Florida.




  He is among the winners of the ninth edition of Discover America, the
  prestigious competition organized by the Chicago Ensemble, as well as the
  First Prize winner of the Keuris Composers Contest 2018.


  He has collaborated with renowned director Marco Bellocchio, who selected him
  to compose the soundtracks for the films Exterior Night (2022) and Kidnapped
  (2023), both presented at the Cannes Film Festival, as well as for
  Bellocchio’s short film If I May (Chapter II), screened out of competition at
  the 81st Venice International Film Festival.


  For the soundtrack of Exterior Night, he was nominated for Best Composer at
  the David di Donatello Awards 2023 and received the Apulia Soundtrack Award
  2023 as Composer of the Year.


  He composed the score for Gianluca Jodice’s film Le Déluge: The Last Days of
  Marie Antoinette (2023), earning nominations at both the Palmarès Européen de
  la Bande Originale and the Nastri d’Argento Awards. He also composed the music
  for Francesca Comencini’s The Time It Takes (2024), presented out of
  competition at the 81st Venice International Film Festival, for which he
  received the Special Prize at the Soundtrack Stars Awards, along with
  nominations at the Nastri d’Argento and the Palmarès Européen de la Bande
  Originale. For A Brief Love Story by Ludovica Rampoldi, he won the Gianni
  Lenoci Award for Best Original Score at Sudestival.


  On the occasion of the 700th anniversary of Marco Polo’s death, he was
  commissioned by Teatro La Fenice in Venice to compose Confini, a work for
  choir and orchestra inspired by the great Venetian traveler. The piece
  premiered on April 19, 2024, performed by the Orchestra and Choir of Teatro La
  Fenice under the direction of Maestro Nicola Luisotti, as part of the
  2023/2024 symphonic season.


  He is also the subject of the documentary Beyond the Mask, directed by Andrea
  Campajola and produced by Edizioni Curci and CIDIM – Italian National Music
  Committee.


  Fabio Massimo Capogrosso’s works are published by CAM Sugar, Edizioni Curci,
  and Plaza Mayor Company

